I spent 3 months trying to learn GenAI.

I failed. Badly.

Not because GenAI is hard.
Because I skipped the foundations.

I was prompt engineering before I understood probability.
Building RAG pipelines before I knew what an embedding actually was.
Copy-pasting LangChain code I didn't understand.

It felt like building a skyscraper on sand.

So I stopped. Went back to basics. And everything clicked.

Here are the 10 things I wish I had learned FIRST:

1️⃣ Python — Not just syntax. Data structures, OOP, NumPy, Pandas.

2️⃣ Linear Algebra — Vectors & matrices ARE neural networks. Learn them.

3️⃣ Calculus — Backpropagation is just the chain rule. That's it.

4️⃣ Statistics & Probability — LLMs don't "think." They predict. Big difference.

5️⃣ ML Fundamentals — Gradient descent, loss functions, overfitting. Non-negotiable.

6️⃣ Deep Learning Basics — Neurons, layers, activation functions. The engine under the hood.

7️⃣ NLP Basics — Tokenization, embeddings, sequence models. The "why" behind LLMs.

8️⃣ Transformer Architecture — Self-attention is the breakthrough. Understand it deeply.

9️⃣ Prompt Engineering — Talk to models intelligently before you build with them.

🔟 APIs & Cloud Basics — REST, JSON, auth. Because GenAI lives in the cloud.

Timeline? 3–6 months.
Worth it? Completely.

Here's the hard truth nobody tells you:

Everyone wants to build the next AI startup.
Almost nobody wants to do the boring work first.

The ones who do?
They're the ones who actually build things that last.

Save this post. Start from step 1.
